WEBVTT

00:01.793 --> 00:04.129
♪ ♪

00:28.027 --> 00:31.406
♪ ♪

00:59.225 --> 01:37.472
♪ ♪

01:37.472 --> 01:42.352
{\an5}<i>GIRL:</i>
<i>I weighed 70 pounds</i>
<i>when my parents checked me in.</i>

01:42.435 --> 01:45.563
And the doctor said

01:45.647 --> 01:47.357
that he would discharge me

01:47.440 --> 01:50.193
when I got up to 85,

01:50.276 --> 01:53.321
and I went nuts.

01:53.404 --> 01:56.616
It's like 85 pounds?

01:56.699 --> 01:57.492
You'll ruin me.

01:57.575 --> 02:00.703
When you hit 85,
<i>were</i> you ruined?

02:00.787 --> 02:02.372
I thought I was.

02:02.455 --> 02:04.874
{\an3}When I went home,
someone said

02:04.958 --> 02:07.168
{\an3}that I was
looking better,

02:07.252 --> 02:08.877
and I stayed in my room
for three days.

02:08.961 --> 02:10.213
What made you finally come out?

02:10.295 --> 02:12.382
I had to get away
from my mother.

02:12.465 --> 02:14.676
(scattered laughter)

02:14.759 --> 02:16.678
I'm not kidding.

02:16.761 --> 02:18.888
Kelly Taylor.

02:18.972 --> 02:22.684
Would you like to tell us
something about yourself?

02:22.767 --> 02:23.643
<i>KELLY:</i>
<i>Mom, I am begging you.</i>

02:23.726 --> 02:26.062
Please don't make me
go back to that place.

02:26.145 --> 02:27.897
The girls there are crazy.

02:27.981 --> 02:29.899
They're not crazy.

02:29.983 --> 02:31.359
Yes, they are.

02:31.442 --> 02:33.444
One of the girls got so thin
that the doctors at the hospital

02:33.528 --> 02:35.738
had to start force-feeding her
through a tube.

02:35.822 --> 02:37.448
Then you know what she did?

02:37.532 --> 02:39.075
She pinched off the tube
because she still wanted

02:39.158 --> 02:41.411
to lose a couple of pounds.

02:41.494 --> 02:44.497
Maybe we should try to
find you another group.

02:44.581 --> 02:46.791
{\an1}I don't want
to be in any group.

02:46.875 --> 02:49.419
Come on, Kelly.

02:49.502 --> 02:51.754
You're a beautiful girl,

02:51.838 --> 02:54.966
but you have got to start
taking care of yourself.

02:55.049 --> 02:56.801
{\an1}Do you know how many models
I knew in New York

02:56.885 --> 02:59.262
{\an1}who ruined their health
and their careers

02:59.345 --> 03:00.930
{\an1}because of
not eating properly?

03:01.014 --> 03:02.390
The last thing I want

03:02.473 --> 03:03.975
is for you to end up
back in the hospital.

03:04.058 --> 03:05.435
{\an3}Me either.

03:05.518 --> 03:07.478
I mean, if this was supposed
to be like Scared Straight

03:07.562 --> 03:10.106
{\an1}or something,
it's working, okay?

03:10.189 --> 03:12.775
{\an1}I even stopped on the way home
and got a mega burger.

03:12.859 --> 03:14.986
It's even got mayonnaise.

03:15.069 --> 03:16.613
This is serious, Kelly.

03:19.407 --> 03:21.284
{\an3}Are your friends giving
you a hard time

03:21.367 --> 03:23.119
{\an3}about being
in this group?

03:23.202 --> 03:24.787
{\an1}No. That's probably because
none of them

03:24.871 --> 03:26.039
know I'm in therapy.

03:26.122 --> 03:27.290
David knows.

03:27.373 --> 03:29.083
Dylan doesn't.

03:29.167 --> 03:30.335
Dylan is in AA.

03:30.418 --> 03:32.754
{\an3}If anybody would
understand, he would.

03:32.837 --> 03:34.839
{\an1}Yeah.
An eating disorder group.

03:34.923 --> 03:35.965
That's very attractive.

03:36.049 --> 03:36.466
Kelly.

03:36.549 --> 03:39.010
Mom, I made a mistake.

03:39.093 --> 03:40.428
I didn't follow directions.

03:40.511 --> 03:41.638
I wasn't trying
to kill myself.

03:41.721 --> 03:42.972
{\an1}I am not like
those other girls.

03:43.056 --> 03:45.808
{\an1}Please?

03:45.892 --> 03:47.518
Okay, if that's
what you want,

03:47.602 --> 03:49.979
{\an3}but only as long
as you keep eating.

03:50.063 --> 03:52.815
I will. I am. See?

03:52.899 --> 03:55.902
Mmm... so good.

04:06.913 --> 04:09.374
(overlapping chatter)

04:11.584 --> 04:13.836
All you seniors who
haven't cast your votes yet

04:13.920 --> 04:15.338
for the senior poll,
you have until third period

04:15.421 --> 04:19.175
to scar your fellow
classmates for life.

04:20.551 --> 04:23.471
Ugh. Like this school needs
another popularity contest.

04:23.554 --> 04:25.014
Don't worry, Bren,

04:25.098 --> 04:26.849
I'm sure you're going to
win Done Most For Class.

04:26.933 --> 04:28.226
I'm serious.

04:28.309 --> 04:29.644
{\an3}You organized
the Pigskin Prom,

04:29.727 --> 04:31.562
the Christmas trip
to Alvarado Street,

04:31.646 --> 04:34.899
{\an3}the orientation program
for the Freshman Buddies.

04:34.983 --> 04:36.442
Brandon, it doesn't matter.

04:36.526 --> 04:37.902
If it's anything like last year,
all the winners

04:37.986 --> 04:39.862
will have known each other
since, like, second grade.

04:39.946 --> 04:43.116
{\an3}I just can't believe
that you care.

04:43.199 --> 04:45.743
You mean you don't think that,
let's say, ten years from now,

04:45.827 --> 04:48.037
you'll get a kick looking back
at the final issue of <i> The Blaze</i>

04:48.121 --> 04:50.707
and remembering that
your friends and your classmates

04:50.790 --> 04:52.542
thought that you were one
of the best and the brightest?

04:52.625 --> 04:56.045
{\an3}Truthfully, Bren, I haven't
given it much thought.

04:56.129 --> 04:57.547
You mean you haven't voted?

04:57.630 --> 05:00.883
Well, yeah, I... I voted.

05:00.967 --> 05:02.051
And you didn't vote
for yourself?

05:02.135 --> 05:04.053
In any category?

05:04.137 --> 05:07.098
I rest my case.

05:10.601 --> 05:11.894
{\an3}Hey, Steve.

05:11.978 --> 05:12.895
Look at my books, man!

05:12.979 --> 05:14.522
{\an1}One of those subhumans
in detention

05:14.605 --> 05:15.606
wrote graffiti all over them.

05:15.690 --> 05:17.942
"Thumper"?

05:18.026 --> 05:20.403
Maybe now I can finally
guilt-trip Mrs. Teasley

05:20.486 --> 05:22.071
{\an1}into admitting
I shouldn't be incarcerated

05:22.155 --> 05:23.239
with any of those lunatics.

05:23.322 --> 05:24.574
8:00 in the morning,

05:24.657 --> 05:26.909
{\an1}it's already turning
into a red-letter day.

05:26.993 --> 05:28.578
{\an1}Man... did you get my message
about Celeste?

05:28.661 --> 05:31.247
Yeah, yeah. How come
she and her friend

05:31.330 --> 05:32.957
{\an3}don't want to go to
the Lakers game with us?

05:33.041 --> 05:34.917
{\an1}She said
she had other plans.

05:35.001 --> 05:36.794
{\an1}First time I asked her out
since our TV dream date,

05:36.878 --> 05:39.422
and she passes...
not a good sign.

05:39.505 --> 05:41.758
Well, to tell you the truth,
I'm feeling a little iffy

05:41.841 --> 05:43.926
about going to
a basketball game myself.

05:44.010 --> 05:45.053
Don't worry, Brandon.

05:45.136 --> 05:46.971
I've got tickets
in the no-gambling section.

05:47.055 --> 05:47.847
If you even think about betting,

05:47.930 --> 05:49.932
the ushers come
and smack you around.

05:50.016 --> 05:50.683
Good.

05:50.767 --> 05:52.769
Think "dateage."

05:52.852 --> 05:54.270
We need two live ones
Friday night,

05:54.353 --> 05:57.106
and bring condoms
because I feel lucky.

05:59.817 --> 06:03.863
(R&amp;B tune playing
over PA system)

06:03.946 --> 06:07.408
{\an3}TEASLEY:
Right. No, I understand.

06:07.492 --> 06:09.994
{\an3}Yes. Believe me,
I don't want

06:10.078 --> 06:12.080
{\an3}your camp program
to fall apart either,

06:12.163 --> 06:14.791
{\an3}but my first responsibility
has to be to the students

06:14.874 --> 06:15.875
of West Beverly High,

06:15.958 --> 06:16.667
{\an3}not Alvarado
Street Elementary.

06:16.751 --> 06:20.588
Yeah. Maybe next year.

06:24.967 --> 06:27.678
Uh... Mrs. Teasley?

06:27.762 --> 06:30.348
(sighs)
Yes, Steven?

06:30.431 --> 06:32.600
I couldn't help hearing what
you said about Alvarado Street.

06:32.683 --> 06:34.352
Are they having some financial
difficulties or something?

06:34.435 --> 06:36.604
To put it mildly.

06:36.687 --> 06:38.940
Actually, our budget
is the one being cut back.

06:39.023 --> 06:41.984
And, apparently, after 14 years,
there are not enough funds

06:42.068 --> 06:45.446
{\an3}to support a summer camp
on our campus anymore.

06:45.530 --> 06:46.489
Oh, that's too bad.
You know, I had such a blast

06:46.572 --> 06:48.825
playing Santa for those kids
last Christmas.

06:48.908 --> 06:51.702
I'm glad you enjoyed yourself.

06:53.913 --> 06:55.331
Did you need something,
Steven?

06:55.414 --> 06:57.875
I guess now is not
a good time, huh?

06:57.959 --> 07:02.213
Sometimes your power of
observation is truly remarkable.

07:11.889 --> 07:13.975
Guess who.

07:14.058 --> 07:16.644
{\an6}It has to be the
most beautiful girl
at West Beverly.

07:16.727 --> 07:18.479
Oh, and, if that's
the way you feel,

07:18.563 --> 07:19.647
how come you didn't
call me back last night?

07:19.730 --> 07:23.192
{\an1}Well, when I'm writing,
I lose all sense of time.

07:23.276 --> 07:24.402
So you say.

07:24.485 --> 07:26.070
What? You think I was playing
around behind your back, Kel?

07:26.154 --> 07:27.113
I was kidding.

07:27.196 --> 07:30.658
{\an1}I know.
It's just that, well,

07:30.741 --> 07:33.828
I've been grappling with some
pretty heavy things, you know?

07:33.911 --> 07:34.745
{\an1}I've been writing
about my dad and...

07:34.829 --> 07:38.040
I know. How's it going?

07:38.124 --> 07:39.667
I don't know.
I mean, I'm too close to it.

07:39.750 --> 07:41.669
I just... I got to make
some last-minute revisions.

07:41.752 --> 07:43.880
So you're almost done?

07:43.963 --> 07:45.006
Almost.

07:45.089 --> 07:46.174
When do I get to read it?

07:46.257 --> 07:48.926
When it's finished,
just like everybody else.

07:49.010 --> 07:49.594
I understand.

07:49.677 --> 07:51.721
I knew you would.

07:51.804 --> 07:53.556
Where are you going?

07:53.639 --> 07:54.599
You're not gonna stick around
to hear the results

07:54.682 --> 07:57.018
of the senior poNo.

07:57.101 --> 07:59.020
{\an6}You're going to
make me go through
this all by myself?

07:59.103 --> 08:00.271
Kel, you're a big girl, okay?

08:00.354 --> 08:00.771
I think you can handle it.

08:00.855 --> 08:02.815
You are a coward!

08:13.659 --> 08:15.953
Is this what I think it is?

08:16.037 --> 08:17.371
Well, it's a rough draft.

08:17.455 --> 08:18.956
I can't believe
you're done already.

08:19.040 --> 08:20.416
It's only the first chapter.

08:20.499 --> 08:23.085
It's mostly, um... well,
it's stuff about my father.

08:23.169 --> 08:24.921
{\an3}I'm sure it'll
require some editing

08:25.004 --> 08:26.756
{\an3}if you want to publish
part of it in <i> The Blaze.</i>

08:26.839 --> 08:28.633
Probably.

08:28.716 --> 08:32.595
Look, if you don't have time
to read it now...

08:32.678 --> 08:34.429
Hey, I'll make time to read it.

08:34.514 --> 08:37.433
Dylan, I'm honored that you're
letting me see this, really.

08:37.515 --> 08:38.558
Thanks.

08:41.854 --> 08:44.023
Hey, Brandon.

08:44.106 --> 08:45.024
{\an3}Do you know when
they're going

08:45.107 --> 08:46.234
{\an3}to announce the results
of the senior poll?

08:46.317 --> 08:48.402
{\an5}Yeah. I think Donna
and David are going
to do it at lunch.

08:48.486 --> 08:50.404
Why?A little.ous?

08:50.488 --> 08:51.739
I just don't want
to be remembered

08:51.822 --> 08:53.658
as the girl who OD'd
on her 18th birthday.

08:53.741 --> 08:56.285
{\an1}Did I tell you it's good
to have you back?

08:56.369 --> 08:58.955
{\an6}Well, I never
really left,
but thanks.

08:59.038 --> 09:00.748
{\an6}STEVE:
Hey! Well, if it isn't
our Most Likely to Succeed

09:00.831 --> 09:02.833
and our Most Beautiful.

09:02.917 --> 09:04.460
{\an3}Very funny.

09:04.543 --> 09:06.003
Hey, I call 'em like I see 'em.

09:06.087 --> 09:07.296
{\an3}Well, you don't
have to humor me.

09:07.380 --> 09:08.965
You haven't looked
in the mirror lately.

09:09.048 --> 09:10.967
Hey, Brando, what's the deal
with the senior poll?

09:11.050 --> 09:12.885
{\an1}I really don't know
any more than you guys do.

09:12.969 --> 09:14.595
Yeah, yeah.

09:14.679 --> 09:16.806
{\an5}Come on, Brandon,
<i>The Blaze</i> runs
the senior poll.

09:16.889 --> 09:17.807
That's right, Kelly.

09:17.890 --> 09:19.475
{\an1}<i>The Blaze</i> does
run the senior poll,

09:19.558 --> 09:20.226
{\an1}but the juniors
who work on the paper

09:20.309 --> 09:21.811
{\an1}keep the ballots
under lock and key

09:21.894 --> 09:24.021
{\an1}so that certain people
won't be tempted

09:24.105 --> 09:26.440
{\an1}to have their friends
stuff the ballots.

09:26.524 --> 09:27.733
Hey, I resemble that remark.

09:27.817 --> 09:29.986
{\an3}Well, Brandon,
you are a definite

09:30.069 --> 09:32.321
{\an3}for Most Likely
to Succeed.

09:32.405 --> 09:34.407
{\an6}And Biggest Flirt
has your name
written all over it.

09:34.490 --> 09:36.033
You think so?

09:36.117 --> 09:37.827
I've seen it firsthand.

09:37.910 --> 09:39.829
{\an3}But if all else fails,
there's always Best Dressed.

09:39.912 --> 09:41.998
{\an1}Guys, I really think
you're blowing

09:42.081 --> 09:43.958
this senior poll thing
way out of proportion.

09:44.041 --> 09:45.459
{\an1}I mean, it's not like the
Nobel Peace Prize or anything.

09:45.543 --> 09:48.004
Gee, I didn't know they gave
a Nobel Prize for Biggest Flirt.

09:48.087 --> 09:49.505
{\an3}(chuckles)

09:49.588 --> 09:51.674
{\an5}DAVID:
And now, the award
for Most Athletic.

09:51.757 --> 09:53.009
And the winner is

09:53.092 --> 09:54.802
Tony Miller,

09:54.885 --> 09:58.723
{\an3}all-league linebacker
and heck of a guy.

09:58.806 --> 10:00.975
And he will share
the honor with...

10:01.058 --> 10:02.727
{\an3}Well, well, we had
a successful

10:02.810 --> 10:04.353
{\an3}write-in campaign
for Olympic

10:04.437 --> 10:06.564
gold medalist Kristi Yamaguchi.

10:06.647 --> 10:07.732
Did I miss much?

10:07.815 --> 10:10.985
Well, Brandon and Andrea won
for Most Likely to Succeed,

10:11.068 --> 10:13.946
David got Most Talented, and
Donna won for Best Dressed.

10:14.030 --> 10:15.865
What about Steve?

10:16.782 --> 10:18.701
Don't even say a word.

10:18.784 --> 10:20.703
Steve, it'Shh!aningless.

10:20.786 --> 10:22.705
I didn't hear
you say that

10:22.788 --> 10:23.831
{\an3}when you won Most Likely
to Succeed, Bran.

10:23.914 --> 10:27.293
{\an5}Biggest Flirt will
be no surprise to
anyone in a skirt.

10:27.376 --> 10:29.503
{\an6}Well, at least there
is some justice
in this world.

10:29.587 --> 10:31.339
It's Tim James.

10:31.422 --> 10:33.883
And, for Flirtette,
Claudette Fletcher.

10:33.966 --> 10:36.719
{\an1}Hey, Steve, Steve,
it's a stupid poll, man.

10:36.802 --> 10:37.678
Your life is not over.

10:37.762 --> 10:38.888
{\an3}No,<i> your</i> life
is not over, okay?

10:38.971 --> 10:41.724
{\an3}I can't even get a date
to the Laker game.

10:41.807 --> 10:42.725
Okay, Done Most for the Class
is next.

10:42.808 --> 10:46.896
And the winners are...

10:46.979 --> 10:48.856
{\an3}Adam Collins
and Leah Mulder.

10:48.939 --> 10:51.859
Leah Mulder?

10:51.942 --> 10:53.861
{\an3}Well, she did convince
Fashion Emporium

10:53.944 --> 10:55.780
{\an3}to give a ten percent discount
to every dues-paying senior.

10:55.863 --> 10:58.908
{\an5}DONNA:
And, Leah, we all thank you
from the bottom of our closets.

10:58.991 --> 11:01.911
Didn't you and Leah go to, like,
elementary school together?

11:01.994 --> 11:05.915
{\an3}Yeah. I've known her
since, like, second grade.

11:05.998 --> 11:07.750
{\an1}Okay, Most Handsome
is next.

11:07.833 --> 11:10.544
{\an1}And, first, I would
like to emphasize

11:10.628 --> 11:11.921
that I personally voted
for my most talented boyfriend,

11:12.004 --> 11:12.963
David, right here.

11:13.047 --> 11:16.384
You're welcome.

11:16.467 --> 11:20.096
But the winner
is Dylan McKay!

11:24.225 --> 11:24.767
Where is Dylan?

11:24.850 --> 11:27.770
Well, you know him.

11:27.853 --> 11:29.939
Anything to avoid
a class activity.

11:30.022 --> 11:35.277
{\an3}And now, West Beverly's
choice for Most Beautiful.

11:35.361 --> 11:36.946
And the winner is

11:37.029 --> 11:41.450
the one and the only--

11:41.534 --> 11:44.120
there she is--
Kelly Taylor.

11:44.203 --> 11:48.249
Congratulations. Go.

11:51.210 --> 11:52.962
There she is, our queen.

11:53.045 --> 11:55.548
Without her king.

11:58.509 --> 12:00.428
ANDREA:
<i>You're a terrific writer.</i>

12:00.511 --> 12:01.971
Well, I'm glad you like it.

12:02.054 --> 12:03.305
When should I send it off
to Doubleday?

12:03.389 --> 12:05.975
Well, actually,
I have a few minor notes,

12:06.058 --> 12:07.977
if you don't mind feedback.

12:08.060 --> 12:10.146
Oh, absolutely. That's why
I gave it to you to read.

12:10.229 --> 12:11.981
But, Zuckerman,
don't be too brutal.

12:12.064 --> 12:14.150
Wouldn't think of it.

12:14.233 --> 12:15.151
Oh, by the way,

12:15.234 --> 12:17.528
congrats
on winning Most Handsome.

12:17.611 --> 12:19.864
Yeah. Now my life
is complete, huh?

12:19.947 --> 12:20.573
(doorbell rings)

12:20.656 --> 12:22.324
Hey, Zuckerman, there's someone

12:22.408 --> 12:23.576
at the door. I got to bail.

12:23.659 --> 12:23.951
I'll callBye. though.

12:30.040 --> 12:31.667
Did somebody here
order takeout?

12:31.750 --> 12:33.836
{\an3}Anybody here
order takeout?

12:33.919 --> 12:36.046
{\an3}Nope. Sorry. You got
the wrong house.

12:36.922 --> 12:38.966
{\an3}You're in
a strange mood.

12:39.049 --> 12:41.969
You always do that to me.

12:42.052 --> 12:43.888
Mm-hmm. Ever
since kindergarten.

12:43.971 --> 12:46.849
{\an1}Remember? You gave me
half your cookie?

12:46.932 --> 12:47.850
I cannot believe you
remember that stuff.

12:47.933 --> 12:50.853
Oh, yeah. I remember
all kinds of things.

12:50.936 --> 12:53.689
{\an1}I've been flashing back
to my memories a lot lately.

12:53.772 --> 12:56.692
You know, I did a pilgrimage
down to the old playground.

12:56.775 --> 12:57.818
{\an1}You should
do it sometime.

12:57.902 --> 12:59.278
{\an1}It gets you back
to your roots in a hurry.

12:59.361 --> 13:00.154
Oh, yeah. That's
just what I need.

13:00.237 --> 13:01.864
The prettiest girl
in Beverly Hills--

13:01.947 --> 13:04.283
that's just what I need.

13:06.076 --> 13:08.579
Dylan, they're
taking the pictures

13:08.662 --> 13:09.788
for the senior poll tomorrow,

13:09.872 --> 13:11.999
{\an3}and they want us to dress
appropriate for the category.

13:12.082 --> 13:14.543
{\an3}So I was thinking
it would be really fun

13:14.627 --> 13:15.920
if you wore, like, a tux,

13:16.003 --> 13:18.339
{\an3}and I wore a really
elegant evening gown.

13:18.422 --> 13:19.089
How about you wear
whatever you want,

13:19.173 --> 13:20.966
{\an1}and I'll wear a bag
over my head?

13:21.050 --> 13:24.053
Seriously.

13:24.136 --> 13:25.721
I am serious.

13:25.804 --> 13:26.055
Dylan...

13:26.138 --> 13:28.140
{\an1}Kelly...

13:28.224 --> 13:29.934
It's bad enough you wouldn't
go to the quad with me

13:30.017 --> 13:31.894
when they announced
the results,

13:31.977 --> 13:33.062
but now to wear a bag over
your head in the picture?

13:33.145 --> 13:35.564
{\an3}What are you
trying to say?

13:35.648 --> 13:37.566
That I think the senior poll
thing is a big joke.

13:37.650 --> 13:38.234
I mean, that's it.
Over and out.

13:38.317 --> 13:40.569
It has nothing to do with you.

13:40.653 --> 13:42.238
{\an6}Well, considering
I'm standing next
to you in the picture,

13:42.321 --> 13:43.906
{\an3}I think it has everything
to do with me.

13:43.989 --> 13:45.533
You know, winning Most Beautiful

13:45.616 --> 13:47.243
is not the most important
thing in my life either.

13:47.326 --> 13:48.285
All right. I know.

13:48.369 --> 13:50.037
{\an3}Okay, let's just...
just forget I said anything

13:50.120 --> 13:53.415
{\an5}and I'll wear the
Fred Astaire suit--
top hat, tails--

13:53.499 --> 13:54.875
and we'll have
a great time.

13:54.959 --> 13:56.418
Don't do my any favors.

13:56.502 --> 13:58.170
Come here.

14:12.017 --> 14:15.271
{\an1}You should have won
the Sexiest Best Lover.

14:17.314 --> 14:19.233
Is that all I am to you?

14:19.316 --> 14:21.110
Are you kidding?

14:21.193 --> 14:23.195
You're a goddess.

14:28.200 --> 14:32.121
{\an3}Have I ever shown
you my favorite room?

14:32.204 --> 14:34.915
Every chance you get.

14:34.999 --> 14:37.126
{\an3}Well, it's different
this time.

14:37.209 --> 14:40.004
Is it?

14:48.387 --> 14:51.140
Mm-mm-mm.

14:51.223 --> 14:54.018
Better safe than sorry.

14:54.101 --> 14:55.144
{\an3}Yeah.

15:05.571 --> 15:08.741
♪ Every now and then ♪

15:08.824 --> 15:11.493
♪ The planets are aligned... ♪

15:11.577 --> 15:13.954
♪ For a little while... ♪

15:14.038 --> 15:14.997
Bren, you got the school
phone directory in here?

15:15.080 --> 15:17.708
Yeah, it's on my desk.

15:17.791 --> 15:18.208
Who are you calling?

15:18.292 --> 15:20.961
Patty Crawford.

15:21.045 --> 15:22.338
Why?

15:22.421 --> 15:23.839
I promised Steve I'd try

15:23.922 --> 15:25.841
{\an1}to round up some dates
for us for Friday night.

15:25.924 --> 15:27.551
But she's such a snob.

15:27.635 --> 15:28.218
{\an1}Well, she did win
Best Dancer.

15:28.302 --> 15:30.638
Rub it in, why don't you?

15:30.721 --> 15:32.014
{\an1}(chuckles)
Come on, Bren,

15:32.097 --> 15:35.017
{\an1}would you rather have won
Most Naive like Donna?

15:35.100 --> 15:37.019
Donna also won
Friendliest and Funniest Laugh.

15:37.102 --> 15:41.857
{\an1}Why is there a University of
Minnesota application in here?

15:41.940 --> 15:44.193
{\an1}I thought we decided we'd both
go to California University.

15:44.276 --> 15:47.571
{\an3}Brandon, I'm just
keeping my options open.

15:47.655 --> 15:49.573
Just because you didn't win
anything in the senior poll.

15:49.657 --> 15:52.368
{\an3}Excuse me, but I filled
out that application

15:52.451 --> 15:53.827
more than a week ago, okay?

15:53.911 --> 15:56.372
{\an1}Bren, you've been
in California so long

15:56.455 --> 15:57.706
{\an1}I think you may
be forgetting

15:57.790 --> 15:58.874
{\an1}what a Midwestern
winter is like.

15:58.957 --> 16:02.044
{\an3}And you've forgotten how many
friends we had back there.

16:02.127 --> 16:04.129
Come on, Bren, when do
you think the last time

16:04.213 --> 16:06.090
{\an1}Darla Hansen even gave you
a passing thought?

16:06.173 --> 16:10.052
{\an3}Oh, about a half hour ago
when she and I were discussing

16:10.135 --> 16:11.845
rooming together
in the same dorm.

16:11.929 --> 16:14.014
Sounds like a lot more than just
keeping your options open.

16:15.140 --> 16:16.392
Have you told Mom and Dad

16:16.475 --> 16:17.893
you're thinking about
moving back there?

16:17.976 --> 16:20.729
Not yet.

16:20.813 --> 16:21.897
{\an3}And I would appreciate
it if you'd let me

16:21.980 --> 16:22.856
{\an3}break it to them
my own way.

16:22.940 --> 16:24.900
It says here
your application deadline...

16:24.983 --> 16:27.152
{\an3}Brandon, don't you have
a phone call to make?

16:31.281 --> 16:34.201
I don't even like
Patty Crawford.

16:34.284 --> 16:35.285
Patty, you really don't
have to explain.

16:35.369 --> 16:37.413
It's okay.

16:37.496 --> 16:38.205
I didn't realize there was
any bad blood

16:38.288 --> 16:40.249
between you and Steve.

16:40.332 --> 16:43.877
Yeah, sure,
maybe some other time.

16:43.961 --> 16:45.295
(chuckles)

16:45.379 --> 16:47.881
Yeah, bye now.

16:47.965 --> 16:48.882
(sighs)

16:48.966 --> 16:50.342
So much for
Most Likely To Succeed.

16:55.305 --> 16:56.265
(door opens)

16:56.348 --> 16:57.266
Hey, Dad.

16:57.349 --> 17:00.060
How's it going?

17:00.144 --> 17:02.896
(groans)

17:05.733 --> 17:07.276
You look fantastic.

17:07.358 --> 17:08.402
Thanks.

17:08.484 --> 17:09.444
One scoop or two?

17:09.528 --> 17:10.319
Make mine a double.

17:10.404 --> 17:13.991
{\an1}Tax time gets more
ridiculous every year.

17:14.074 --> 17:14.782
What's your excuse?

17:14.867 --> 17:16.952
{\an3}Well, it's kind of
embarrassing.

17:17.035 --> 17:18.746
{\an3}Steve has some tickets to
the Laker game tomorrow night,

17:18.829 --> 17:20.204
{\an3}and we can't seem to find
anyone to go with us.

17:20.289 --> 17:23.791
{\an3}So, if you and Mom
aren't busy...

17:25.669 --> 17:26.587
That's the nicest invitation
I've had all year.

17:26.670 --> 17:30.090
{\an1}What's the nicest invitation
you've had all year?

17:30.174 --> 17:32.801
Your son just invited us
to the Laker game

17:32.885 --> 17:34.845
{\an1}with him and Steve
tomorrow night.

17:34.928 --> 17:36.305
{\an1}Hey, that sounds like
a lot of fun.

17:36.388 --> 17:38.807
The problem is I've got
a million returns due

17:38.891 --> 17:39.975
by the 15th.

17:40.058 --> 17:41.810
{\an3}Hey, if you guys
can't go, that's okay,

17:41.894 --> 17:42.269
{\an3}I totally understand.
No problem.

17:42.352 --> 17:45.189
Jim, come on.

17:45.272 --> 17:46.815
Oh, you're right.

17:46.899 --> 17:48.817
{\an5}The hell with it.
I haven't been to
a game all season.

17:48.901 --> 17:51.612
It really means a lot to me
that you, uh,

17:51.695 --> 17:53.197
you still want to spend a Friday
night with your old man.

17:53.280 --> 17:54.364
{\an1}CINDY:
Oh, and thank Steve for us.

17:54.448 --> 17:57.659
I sure will.

17:57.743 --> 17:59.745
(chuckles)

18:04.708 --> 18:06.335
{\an3}Well, if I didn't
talk to David,

18:06.418 --> 18:08.921
I wouldn't know anything
that's going on with you.

18:09.004 --> 18:10.714
Congratulations,
Most Beautiful.

18:10.798 --> 18:12.549
I wanted to surprise you.

18:12.633 --> 18:14.092
So I raided your closet.

18:16.261 --> 18:18.347
Well, what do you think?

18:18.430 --> 18:19.848
Perfect.

18:19.932 --> 18:22.184
Yeah. I just feel like something
is a little off.

18:22.267 --> 18:26.021
Well, if you're going to
wear a dress like that,

18:26.105 --> 18:28.482
{\an3}you've got to
upgrade those eyes.

18:28.565 --> 18:30.818
{\an3}Like mother,
like daughter.

18:30.901 --> 18:34.196
Invisible eyelashes
and pale as a ghost.

18:34.279 --> 18:36.406
That's better.

18:36.490 --> 18:38.867
See, I do come in handy
every once in a while.

18:38.951 --> 18:40.410
{\an3}I could give you a few
tips, if you want.

18:40.494 --> 18:42.037
No, I've got to go.

18:42.120 --> 18:43.372
It's just a school picture.

18:43.455 --> 18:46.166
Well, that is what I thought
about my high school picture,

18:46.250 --> 18:47.543
until it got picked up

18:47.626 --> 18:50.671
in a "Girls of Ohio" spread
in <i> Esquire,</i>

18:50.754 --> 18:53.382
{\an1}and the next thing I knew
I was modeling in New York.

18:53.465 --> 18:54.216
{\an3}Oh, I don't want
to be a model.

18:54.299 --> 18:55.217
Of course not.

18:55.300 --> 18:57.678
{\an1}I wouldn't wish that
on anybody.

18:57.761 --> 18:59.680
{\an1}But there's nothing wrong
with looking like one,

18:59.763 --> 19:01.890
{\an3}is there?

19:01.974 --> 19:04.226
Now, what do you think?

19:04.309 --> 19:07.104
That's nice.

19:07.187 --> 19:08.605
I used to love to
put your hair up

19:08.689 --> 19:10.023
when you were little.

19:11.817 --> 19:13.694
Yeah, maybe I should
wear it up then.

19:13.777 --> 19:14.278
{\an3}Well, it would
show off your neck.

19:14.361 --> 19:16.405
Highlight your angle.

19:16.488 --> 19:17.573
My angle?

19:17.656 --> 19:20.325
{\an3}Kelly, every woman needs to
know how to hold her head

19:20.409 --> 19:23.412
{\an3}so she looks her
absolute best.

19:23.495 --> 19:24.872
{\an3}For a model that is
the difference between

19:24.955 --> 19:27.207
$10,000 a day
and nothing.

19:27.291 --> 19:28.041
Don't worry.

19:28.125 --> 19:30.502
{\an3}We will make you
look unforgettable.

19:34.339 --> 19:36.633
DAVID (over PA):
Attention senior poll winners,

19:36.717 --> 19:38.969
last call for photos
in the quad.

19:39.052 --> 19:40.304
Be there or be square.

19:40.387 --> 19:41.763
(Steve laughing)

19:41.847 --> 19:44.308
Ah, so is this how you
dress for success?

19:44.391 --> 19:45.976
That's what they tell me.

19:46.059 --> 19:47.603
{\an3}You know, I think the <i> Blaze</i>
should've had a category

19:47.686 --> 19:48.937
{\an3}for Most Time Spent
in Detention.

19:49.021 --> 19:50.939
No, no, it's cool.
It's old news.

19:51.023 --> 19:52.232
What I'd like to know is,

19:52.316 --> 19:53.775
{\an3}who's going to the game
with us tonight?

19:53.859 --> 19:55.611
{\an1}I kind of wanted to talk
to you about that.

19:55.694 --> 19:56.778
Come here.

19:56.862 --> 19:58.947
{\an1}Oh, oh, don't even
tell me you struck out?

19:59.031 --> 20:00.616
{\an3}No, no, no, I
didn't strike out.

20:00.699 --> 20:03.619
{\an3}I somehow managed
to invite my parents.

20:03.702 --> 20:05.162
You're kidding?

20:05.245 --> 20:07.581
No, I'm not kidding,
it just slipped out.

20:07.664 --> 20:09.791
{\an3}Look, you don't
mind, do you?

20:09.875 --> 20:11.293
{\an1}Brandon, yeah,
I kind of do mind!

20:11.376 --> 20:12.794
{\an3}Look, you shouldn't have
put me in charge

20:12.878 --> 20:14.421
of organizing your
social life, Steve.

20:14.504 --> 20:16.256
{\an1}Obviously.

20:16.340 --> 20:17.799
How could you
do this to me?

20:17.883 --> 20:18.634
{\an1}Don't I have enough
trouble as it is?

20:18.717 --> 20:21.136
{\an3}Steve, I hate to
inform you of this,

20:21.219 --> 20:22.930
{\an3}but some jerk defacing
your school books

20:23.013 --> 20:24.139
and not winning
the senior poll

20:24.222 --> 20:26.767
{\an3}are not exactly the major
issues of our time.

20:26.850 --> 20:27.976
(sighs)

20:28.060 --> 20:29.311
No, it's okay.

20:29.394 --> 20:31.939
{\an1}We'll go to the game with
your folks on one condition--

20:32.022 --> 20:33.774
{\an1}you sit next
to your mother.

20:33.857 --> 20:36.068
{\an3}What's wrong with
my mother?

20:43.867 --> 20:45.619
And I thought I was gonna
be able to sneak in by myself

20:45.702 --> 20:47.996
and put on some mascara
before the photo session.

20:48.080 --> 20:50.499
{\an1}Oh, well,
take a number.

20:50.582 --> 20:51.375
{\an1}You think I look
too naive?

20:51.458 --> 20:53.377
I think you look adorable.

20:53.460 --> 20:56.672
And I loved your outfit
as Best Dressed.

20:56.755 --> 20:57.673
It was great.

20:57.756 --> 20:58.507
You're welcome.

20:58.590 --> 21:01.343
{\an1}Well, I don't think
you need mascara.

21:01.426 --> 21:02.636
You have great eyes.

21:02.719 --> 21:04.179
You have great everything.

21:04.262 --> 21:05.347
Only if I work at it.

21:05.430 --> 21:07.516
{\an3}Oh, yeah, Kelly Taylor
a total car chaser.

21:07.599 --> 21:10.811
{\an1}You have to admit
my eyelashes are invisible.

21:10.894 --> 21:12.187
I'm as pale as a ghost.

21:12.270 --> 21:13.605
I have no cheekbones,

21:13.689 --> 21:15.524
and my nose is never
gonna be quite right.

21:15.607 --> 21:17.192
{\an3}Oh, will you can
the self-pity?

21:17.275 --> 21:18.360
Like every girl
in this school

21:18.443 --> 21:19.820
wouldn't trade places
with you in a second.

21:19.903 --> 21:21.029
I'll trade.

21:21.113 --> 21:21.655
{\an1}Let them spend
their whole lives

21:21.738 --> 21:23.573
trying to look unforgettable

21:23.657 --> 21:24.574
{\an1}just so they can never
be taken seriously.

21:24.658 --> 21:26.535
You're being ridiculous.

21:26.618 --> 21:27.703
Am I?

21:27.786 --> 21:29.538
{\an1}I just said that nobody
takes me seriously

21:29.621 --> 21:31.206
{\an1}and you didn't take me
seriously, did you?

21:31.289 --> 21:33.166
Well, from what Dylan
has been writing,

21:33.250 --> 21:35.168
{\an1}I would say he takes you
very seriously.

21:37.295 --> 21:39.548
{\an1}You've read
Dylan's manuscript?

21:39.631 --> 21:40.424
{\an3}Mm-hmm.
Oh, it's terrific.

21:52.477 --> 21:53.395
{\an3}Thank you.

21:53.478 --> 21:54.855
Uh, clowns, please.

21:55.981 --> 21:57.733
I don't know, McKay.

21:57.816 --> 21:58.734
{\an3}I think you should have
won Best Dressed.

21:58.817 --> 22:01.403
Come on, man, this is
Kelly's idea, all right?

22:01.486 --> 22:02.779
She wanted to make
a fashion statement,

22:02.863 --> 22:04.906
so this is my homage
to Fred Astaire.

22:04.990 --> 22:05.949
Except he could dance.

22:06.033 --> 22:07.743
You Dylan....

22:07.826 --> 22:08.577
Yeah, hey, good looking.

22:08.660 --> 22:10.203
Now, is this what
you haNo.n mind?

22:10.287 --> 22:11.413
Can I talk to you?

22:11.496 --> 22:13.081
Hey, Dylan,
don't go too far away.

22:13.165 --> 22:14.750
You're on deck.

22:14.833 --> 22:15.584
What's the matter?

22:15.667 --> 22:18.420
{\an1}When do I get to read
your manuscript?

22:18.503 --> 22:19.713
{\an3}I told you,
when it's ready.

22:19.796 --> 22:20.964
{\an1}Why is it done enough
for Andrea to read?

22:21.048 --> 22:23.759
Because she's my editor.

22:23.842 --> 22:25.761
{\an6}And she's the one that
got me into writing
in the first place.

22:25.844 --> 22:27.971
Then why don't you
go to bed with her?

22:28.055 --> 22:30.432
{\an3}What are you...
what are you saying?

22:30.515 --> 22:31.600
I'm saying that I really resent
being good enough to sleep with,

22:31.683 --> 22:33.935
{\an1}but not good enough
to show your writing to.

22:34.019 --> 22:34.936
{\an3}Okay, I will show it
to you, all right?

22:35.020 --> 22:36.146
{\an1}Not because
you value my opinion,

22:36.229 --> 22:38.106
only because you want
me to shut up, right?

22:38.190 --> 22:39.191
Hey, McKay, where are you going?

22:39.274 --> 22:40.484
Hey, I'll be right back.

22:40.567 --> 22:41.818
Kel, listen, I don't know
what's going on with you,

22:41.902 --> 22:42.861
but I do value your opinion.

22:42.944 --> 22:45.739
{\an3}No, you value the way I look
and the way I dress

22:45.822 --> 22:47.449
{\an3}and the fact that
I have sex with you.

22:47.532 --> 22:48.742
{\an3}But you don't listen
to a thing I say.

22:48.825 --> 22:49.910
I don't listen to you?

22:49.993 --> 22:51.286
{\an1}Who was I listening to
when I picked up

22:51.369 --> 22:53.121
{\an1}this ridiculous hat
and this stupid cane?!

22:53.205 --> 22:54.790
I don't want to have
this picture taken anyway.

22:54.873 --> 22:56.583
Fine, then we
won't take it.

22:56.666 --> 22:59.169
I want to take it.

22:59.252 --> 23:00.295
Well, then don't forget
to smile for the camera.

23:11.264 --> 23:13.225
{\an3}JACKIE:
Dylan called, honey.

23:13.308 --> 23:14.559
Who cares?

23:17.312 --> 23:18.438
(door slams)

23:24.402 --> 23:26.988
So, I'm dying to know,
how'd the session go?

23:27.072 --> 23:29.199
I didn't get the stupid picture
taken, okay?

23:29.282 --> 23:30.659
{\an1}After all that work
we went through?

23:30.742 --> 23:32.661
You went through.

23:32.744 --> 23:33.662
{\an3}I just sat there,
hating every minute of it.

23:33.745 --> 23:35.997
{\an1}Then you should have
said something.

23:36.081 --> 23:38.834
I couldn't, you were too
busy putting my hair up

23:38.917 --> 23:40.210
and criticizing my makeup.

23:40.293 --> 23:41.837
I did nothing
of the kind.

23:41.920 --> 23:42.671
Yeah, but you
I saididn't mean it.rfect.

