23:45.090 --> 23:46.842
You know, when I was 12,
it was

23:46.925 --> 23:48.343
"Of course you're pretty,
honey bun,

23:48.426 --> 23:50.011
but let's see if Weight Watchers
can do the trick."

23:50.095 --> 23:51.680
We're back to
And when I turned 15,

23:51.763 --> 23:53.014
you didn't get me a cake
like a normal mom,

23:53.098 --> 23:54.975
You begged me for it!.

23:55.058 --> 23:56.518
Only after you
told me I needed it.

23:56.601 --> 23:57.853
That is absolutely not true.

23:57.936 --> 23:59.521
{\an1}From the time you were
old enough to read,

23:59.604 --> 24:01.231
all you could talk about
was beauty and fashion.

24:01.314 --> 24:02.858
That is because that's
all you ever talked about,

24:02.941 --> 24:05.485
when you weren't passed out,
or out picking up one-nighters.

24:05.569 --> 24:06.862
Okay, I'm a terrible human being
and I've ruined your life.

24:06.945 --> 24:08.655
No, I don't want
to hear anything.

24:08.738 --> 24:10.824
WFine, then I will shut up.

24:10.907 --> 24:12.284
{\an3}But first I want to
thank you for teaching me

24:12.367 --> 24:12.993
{\an3}how to be shallow
and insincere.

24:13.076 --> 24:14.995
{\an1}Why are you trying
to hurt me?

24:15.078 --> 24:16.955
{\an3}Oh, God, I am so
sick of everything,

24:17.038 --> 24:18.874
You are screaming.

24:18.957 --> 24:20.167
Yeah, and it's about time.

24:20.250 --> 24:21.877
Kelly, get back here.
Where are you going?

24:31.803 --> 24:32.596
Brandon, hi.
How are you?

24:32.679 --> 24:34.639
{\an3}Fine. Late. Crazed.
How are you?

24:34.723 --> 24:36.600
{\an1}Okay, I know this is going
to sound a little weird,

24:36.683 --> 24:39.019
but I need to borrow $50.

24:39.102 --> 24:39.769
CINDY:
Brandon...!

24:39.853 --> 24:41.396
Steve's here.

24:41.479 --> 24:43.190
I'll be right down, Mom.

24:43.273 --> 24:44.900
{\an1}Brandon, can't you
help me out?

24:44.983 --> 24:46.693
{\an3}Brenda, all I have in
the world is ten dollars.

24:46.776 --> 24:48.904
Thanks, but I need $50.

24:48.987 --> 24:49.905
Why?

24:49.988 --> 24:51.615
{\an1}Minnesota requires
a $50 deposit

24:51.698 --> 24:53.742
{\an1}before they'll process
an out-of-state application.

24:53.825 --> 24:57.746
So, why don't you just hit
Mom and Dad up for a check?

24:57.829 --> 24:59.623
{\an3}You haven't told them
you're applying there yet?

24:59.706 --> 25:02.042
{\an1}I just didn't want
to get into

25:02.125 --> 25:03.418
a big family powwow
over this thing...

25:03.501 --> 25:04.794
Well, eventually they're
going to find out, Bren.

25:04.878 --> 25:06.046
{\an3}When were you planning
on telling them?

25:06.129 --> 25:07.422
{\an3}After you'd already
been accepted?

25:07.505 --> 25:08.965
{\an1}I just haven't found
a good time to bring it up.

25:09.049 --> 25:10.759
Well, now is definitely
not a good time, okay.

25:10.842 --> 25:12.093
{\an3}Because Dad is not
even home yet,

25:12.177 --> 25:13.178
and we're already
late for the game.

25:13.261 --> 25:15.805
{\an1}The application has to be
postmarked before midnight.

25:15.889 --> 25:16.806
You're killing me, Bren.

25:16.890 --> 25:20.268
Do you think Steve
would lend me $50?

25:22.520 --> 25:24.105
He just pulled in.

25:24.189 --> 25:25.273
Good.

25:26.191 --> 25:27.275
Sorry, I'm late.

25:27.359 --> 25:28.401
I got waylaid at the office.

25:28.485 --> 25:29.945
It's okay, honey. No rush.

25:30.028 --> 25:31.738
Yeah, no rush, who wants to be
there for the opening tip-off?

25:31.821 --> 25:34.741
{\an1}Hey, hey, hey, I know
a great shortcut, okay?

25:34.824 --> 25:35.700
Hey, Dad, let's go.

25:35.784 --> 25:38.286
I'll be down in two seconds.

25:38.370 --> 25:39.537
Fine.

25:42.040 --> 25:42.832
You want to have a little
something to eat before we go?

25:42.916 --> 25:46.628
{\an3}Yeah. Your Mom made
fresh fruit cups.

25:46.711 --> 25:47.796
No thanks, Mom.

25:47.879 --> 25:50.632
I think we'll just get a
couple dogs at the game.

25:50.715 --> 25:51.758
{\an3}If we ever get
to the game.

25:51.841 --> 25:52.842
{\an1}He'll be down
in two seconds.

25:53.718 --> 25:56.680
{\an3}(knocking)

25:56.763 --> 25:57.806
Dad?

25:57.889 --> 25:58.974
Hi, honey.

25:59.057 --> 26:00.767
Can I talk to you
for two seconds?

26:00.850 --> 26:02.811
I'd like to apply to the
University of Minnesota.

26:05.063 --> 26:08.817
{\an4}JIM:
Cindy, can you please come
up here for two seconds?

26:08.900 --> 26:11.111
I'll just be two seconds.

26:11.194 --> 26:13.655
Two seconds,
two seconds,

26:13.738 --> 26:14.739
{\an3}what is two seconds,
Walsh-speak for an eternity?

26:14.823 --> 26:17.492
Steve, it only takes
20 minutes to get to the Forum.

26:17.575 --> 26:19.995
We've got plenty of
Man...o get there.

26:20.078 --> 26:22.038
(car horns honking)

26:22.122 --> 26:23.832
Come on, damn it!

26:23.915 --> 26:25.000
Jim, relax.

26:25.083 --> 26:26.835
Hell of a shortcut.

26:26.918 --> 26:28.712
{\an3}Shut up, will ya? We're in
a family crisis, okay?

26:28.795 --> 26:31.464
{\an3}I'm just so fed
up with her.

26:31.548 --> 26:34.509
How could she spring this on us
at the last minute like this?

26:34.592 --> 26:36.011
{\an3}Are we that
unapproachable?

26:36.094 --> 26:37.345
{\an3}We're her parents,
for God's sake.

26:37.429 --> 26:39.514
She's just keeping
her options open.

26:39.597 --> 26:41.349
An option that's

26:41.433 --> 26:42.892
{\an1}2,000 miles
away from us.

26:42.976 --> 26:44.978
Honey, don't take
it so personally.

26:45.061 --> 26:45.854
All she heard growing up

26:45.937 --> 26:47.981
{\an1}was what a fabulous
school Minnesota was.

26:48.064 --> 26:50.650
(car horn blaring)

26:50.734 --> 26:51.860
{\an3}Every
lousy driver

26:51.943 --> 26:53.361
{\an3}in Los Angeles is on
the road tonight.

26:53.445 --> 26:56.489
Maybe we should go back.

26:56.573 --> 26:57.741
{\an1}JIM:
No, no, no.

26:57.824 --> 26:59.659
We're almost there.

26:59.743 --> 27:01.369
{\an1}And besides, don't they have
a big show at half-time?

27:01.453 --> 27:04.914
{\an1}Uh, that's football,
Mrs. Walsh.

27:04.998 --> 27:07.042
Oh.

27:07.125 --> 27:09.002
{\an1}You're definitely
sitting next to her.

27:17.927 --> 27:20.388
Steve, great seats!

27:20.472 --> 27:22.599
Oh, thanks a lot.

27:22.682 --> 27:23.892
Oh man, the game's already
in the refrigerator.

27:23.975 --> 27:25.518
{\an5}BRANDON:
Yeah, and that's where
I'm going to put you

27:25.602 --> 27:26.603
{\an1}if you don't
chill out, okay?

27:26.686 --> 27:27.437
Who sits where?

27:27.520 --> 27:28.772
Why don't you just
sit there, Mom?

27:28.855 --> 27:30.398
{\an1}Steve likes to sit
on the aisle.

27:30.482 --> 27:32.067
Well, don't you want to
sit next to your father?

27:32.150 --> 27:35.028
{\an1}No, no, that's okay. I'd much
rather sit next to you.

27:35.111 --> 27:37.405
{\an3}Excuse me, is
this your seat?

27:37.489 --> 27:39.282
(laughing):
No. This is his seat.

27:39.366 --> 27:40.575
<i>This</i> is my seat.

27:40.658 --> 27:41.743
{\an3}Okay.

27:41.826 --> 27:42.160
Congratulations.

27:42.243 --> 27:43.036
Before the game,

27:43.119 --> 27:45.955
seat number GG 35 was
picked at random

27:46.039 --> 27:50.627
{\an3}to try to make a half-court
shot at half-time for $10,000.

27:50.710 --> 27:52.921
(laughter, whooping)

27:53.004 --> 27:54.297
Go for it, son!

27:54.381 --> 27:56.299
But I'll need to see
your ticket stub first.

27:56.383 --> 27:57.967
Yeah, sure.

27:58.051 --> 28:01.262
There it is...

28:01.346 --> 28:06.142
{\an3}I'm sorry.
I need GG 35.

28:06.226 --> 28:07.602
{\an3}JIM:
We've got it.

28:07.685 --> 28:08.269
BYSTANDER:
He's got the wrong ticket.

28:08.353 --> 28:12.148
G... GG 35!
Buddy, buddy!

28:12.232 --> 28:14.776
I've been waiting all
my life for this shot!

28:14.859 --> 28:15.985
Go get 'em brother.

28:18.988 --> 28:22.867
CHEERLEADERS:
Go... go... Lakers!

28:28.039 --> 28:28.915
Hey.

28:28.998 --> 28:31.418
{\an3}Man, I'm glad
to see you.

28:31.501 --> 28:32.961
Dude, are you psyched?

28:33.044 --> 28:34.337
{\an3}Psyched? I'm a little freaked
out, thank you very much.

28:34.421 --> 28:35.463
Hey, Steve, you
got to relax, man.

28:35.547 --> 28:36.381
I'm trying to relax.

28:36.464 --> 28:38.466
I've never been any
good under pressure.

28:38.550 --> 28:39.968
{\an5}Oh, don't worry about it.
Nobody expect you to hit
a basket from half-court.

28:40.051 --> 28:42.846
{\an3}Are you kidding? These
people are brutal out here!

28:42.929 --> 28:44.973
{\an3}You make one air ball,
and they boo you.

28:45.056 --> 28:47.308
{\an1}Okay, you're up
in about four minutes.

28:47.392 --> 28:50.311
{\an1}Why don't we go out
and loosen up.

28:50.395 --> 28:51.771
{\an3}The worse part
of this whole thing

28:51.855 --> 28:53.648
is seeing
Jack Nicholson going...

28:54.065 --> 28:55.984
Come on Buddy,
you're not going to choke.

28:56.067 --> 28:57.986
Listen, if I die
of embarrassment,

28:58.069 --> 29:00.321
tell my mother I love her.

29:00.405 --> 29:01.114
Come back with a check
for ten grand,

29:01.197 --> 29:03.158
you can tell her
yourself, okay?

29:06.077 --> 29:08.037
All right, go for it!

29:08.121 --> 29:09.038
{\an1}Ten grand!
Ten grand!

29:09.122 --> 29:11.374
{\an1}You think he'll hit
the backboard?

29:11.458 --> 29:13.209
{\an3}Eight-to-one he
throws up a brick.

29:13.293 --> 29:15.503
I thought we'd quit gambling.

29:15.587 --> 29:17.005
We did.

29:17.088 --> 29:18.965
Brandon, wait a minute.

29:19.048 --> 29:21.843
{\an3}Did your sister tell you she
was applying to Minnesota?

29:21.926 --> 29:24.804
{\an1}Yeah, but she didn't
exactly confide in me.

29:24.888 --> 29:26.014
{\an3}Hmm. If she hadn't
needed a check,

29:26.097 --> 29:29.350
{\an3}I don't know when we would
have heard about it.

29:29.434 --> 29:32.604
She just didn't want you to read
too much into it, that's all.

29:32.687 --> 29:35.190
{\an3}I know, but that doesn't
mean she has to shut us out.

29:35.273 --> 29:38.026
You know, you and your sister
are going to be 18 this summer.

29:38.109 --> 29:40.028
{\an3}You're going to be making
a lot of decisions

29:40.111 --> 29:43.364
that your mother and I might
not necessarily agree with,

29:43.448 --> 29:46.993
{\an3}but that doesn't mean we're
going to turn on you.

29:47.076 --> 29:49.204
Let's go watch Steve.

29:49.287 --> 29:51.581
Uh, Dad...

29:51.664 --> 29:54.000
{\an3}I don't quite know how
to tell you this...

29:54.083 --> 29:57.045
{\an3}but, uh, the whole sports
betting thing...

29:58.421 --> 30:01.090
{\an3}I really didn't quit
when I was ahead.

30:01.174 --> 30:04.219
{\an3}I actually got into a little
trouble with a bookie.

30:04.302 --> 30:05.261
A little trouble?

30:05.345 --> 30:07.931
Actually, it was
a lot of trouble.

30:08.014 --> 30:10.350
Nat had to bail me out.

30:10.433 --> 30:11.976
(sighs)

30:12.060 --> 30:14.729
Great, you can't
talk to me either?

30:14.812 --> 30:16.231
No, I can. I just...

30:16.314 --> 30:18.942
{\an3}I just didn't want you
to know I was screwing up.

30:19.025 --> 30:23.571
{\an1}Brandon, no matter
how bad you screw up,

30:23.655 --> 30:25.907
you're still my only son,

30:25.990 --> 30:28.076
and don't you ever forget that,

30:28.159 --> 30:31.037
{\an1}or I'll have to whip your butt
in a game of one-on-one.

30:31.120 --> 30:33.456
Okay, I'm sorry.

30:33.540 --> 30:36.042
We'll talk about it later.

30:36.125 --> 30:38.086
Right now, we'd better
not miss Steve's shot.

30:38.169 --> 30:41.089
{\an3}He'd never forgive
either of us.

30:41.172 --> 30:44.467
{\an5}(over speaker)
Good evening ladies and
gentlemen, this is Chick Hearn,

30:44.551 --> 30:46.427
and it's time now
for our half-court shot.

30:46.511 --> 30:48.888
This evening, we have
Steve Sanders at mid court,

30:48.972 --> 30:50.932
and if Steve can make this shot,

30:51.015 --> 30:55.979
he'll walk away with a suitcase
full of money-- $10,000.

31:00.149 --> 31:01.276
Yay, Steve!

31:01.359 --> 31:03.820
Yes! Go for it!

31:11.035 --> 31:12.620
Go for it!

31:14.163 --> 31:17.375
Oh great, Dyan Cannon.
Come on...

31:24.048 --> 31:26.009
(ball dribbles)

31:30.221 --> 31:33.975
{\an1}SPECTATOR:
Air ball!

31:45.945 --> 31:47.363
Yahoo!

31:49.574 --> 31:51.451
HEARN:
What a shot!

31:51.534 --> 31:52.035
Ladies and gentlemen,
Steve Sanders

31:52.118 --> 31:56.664
has just won $10,000!

31:56.748 --> 32:01.002
Steve, when you decide to turn
pro, you let us know.

32:03.630 --> 32:06.799
{\an3}Yes! Go!

32:09.969 --> 32:12.347
I can't believe it!

32:16.601 --> 32:18.311
DAVID:
<i>I mean, I've lived with Kelly</i>

32:18.394 --> 32:21.064
{\an3}for awhile now,
and she can get moody,

32:21.147 --> 32:23.524
but I've never heard
her get that upset.

32:23.608 --> 32:26.361
{\an5}I mean, Jackie hasn't
come out of her room
since Kelly took off.

32:26.444 --> 32:27.362
I feel bad for Jackie,

32:27.445 --> 32:30.698
'cause it's not her that
Kelly's mad at, it's me.

32:30.782 --> 32:32.367
But she's definitely
down on Jackie, too.

32:32.450 --> 32:34.035
She had a few things
on her mind lately.

32:34.118 --> 32:35.161
Well, it's nice to feel

32:35.244 --> 32:37.163
like you can take care
of everything yourself,

32:37.246 --> 32:39.165
{\an3}but I still feel Kelly
was better off

32:39.248 --> 32:41.751
{\an3}staying in that
eating disorder group.

32:41.834 --> 32:42.877
What group?

32:42.960 --> 32:43.294
She didn't tell you about it?

32:43.378 --> 32:44.253
No, she didn't.

32:44.337 --> 32:47.423
(sighs)

32:47.507 --> 32:49.008
I didn't know it was a secret.

32:49.092 --> 32:51.010
Neither did I, David.

32:51.094 --> 32:52.720
Listen man, I thought
about going after her,

32:52.804 --> 32:53.888
but I felt that if

32:53.971 --> 32:56.683
{\an6}I were that worked up,
I'd just want to
be left alone.

32:56.766 --> 32:58.393
My guess is she went
down to the beach.

32:58.476 --> 33:04.065
No, I don't think
that's where she went.

33:10.446 --> 33:13.991
<i>Hmm. The old playground.</i>

33:17.328 --> 33:20.415
I knew you'd be here.

33:20.498 --> 33:24.210
I used to push you
on this same swing.

33:24.293 --> 33:26.087
So you could look
up my dress.

33:26.170 --> 33:30.717
That wasn't me.

33:30.800 --> 33:33.928
{\an3}Kel, I remember the time
you jumped off this thing.

33:34.011 --> 33:37.515
{\an6}You skinned your knee,
but you didn't want
anyone to see you cry,

33:37.598 --> 33:40.601
{\an3}so you just stood there
bleeding, trying to smile.

33:43.438 --> 33:47.608
{\an3}It's not that easy
anymore, Dylan.

33:47.692 --> 33:51.779
So why don't you just do me and
everybody else a big favor

33:51.863 --> 33:53.865
and go back to Brenda?

33:53.948 --> 33:55.867
Is that really
what you want?

33:55.950 --> 33:57.285
{\an1}It doesn't matter
what I really want.

33:57.368 --> 34:00.955
{\an1}I'm just a stupid
blonde bitch

34:01.038 --> 34:02.290
I disagree.eally worth it.

34:02.373 --> 34:06.544
Then why don't you
talk to my father,

34:06.627 --> 34:09.922
who never bothers
to call me anymore.

34:10.005 --> 34:12.967
Or my mom, who probably
hates me right now.

34:13.050 --> 34:15.011
{\an1}(laughs)
Or all the guys

34:15.094 --> 34:17.388
I put out for in the tenth grade
and never heard from again.

34:17.472 --> 34:19.599
{\an1}Or why don't you
talk to Brenda

34:19.681 --> 34:21.516
and find out how it really feels

34:21.601 --> 34:24.270
to have somebody you trust
go behind your back

34:24.353 --> 34:26.272
and steal your boyfriend
from you.

34:26.355 --> 34:27.857
That's not how it happened.

34:27.940 --> 34:29.275
That's not even close, Kel.

34:29.358 --> 34:30.275
That's part of what
I've been writing about.

34:32.360 --> 34:35.864
{\an1}(laughing):
Yes.

34:35.947 --> 34:39.827
{\an1}Thank you for reminding me
about that.

34:39.911 --> 34:42.121
Kelly, do you have any idea

34:42.205 --> 34:44.373
how difficult it is for me
to share that with anybody?

34:44.456 --> 34:47.627
{\an1}You're not the only one
who wants to end up

34:47.710 --> 34:50.505
{\an1}as more than just Best
Looking in the stupid poll.

34:50.588 --> 34:53.299
You are already so much more
than that, and you know it.

34:53.382 --> 34:55.676
How do I know it?

34:55.760 --> 34:57.970
Who ever tells me that I'm smart
or even worth knowing?

34:58.054 --> 34:59.388
{\an1}We are

34:59.472 --> 35:01.849
two little kids
who had to walk home

35:01.933 --> 35:03.392
from school by ourselves,

35:03.476 --> 35:05.937
{\an1}because our parents
forgot to pick us up.

35:06.020 --> 35:07.480
I guess we're both basket cases.

35:07.563 --> 35:09.232
No...

35:09.315 --> 35:10.316
we're soul mates.

35:12.318 --> 35:14.862
I-If you hadn't called me
that day at the marina,

35:14.946 --> 35:16.697
<i>I</i> would've fried in that car.

35:16.781 --> 35:18.282
And I miss Jack--
I miss him...

35:18.366 --> 35:21.285
I miss him more than
I can tell you, but I'm not...

35:21.369 --> 35:23.037
I'm not unhappy to be alive.

35:23.120 --> 35:26.165
And most of my life,
I couldn't say that.

35:26.249 --> 35:27.875
I care what you think.

35:27.959 --> 35:29.210
I don't care that you're in
an eating disorder group, Kel.

35:29.293 --> 35:33.047
If you said that you never
wanted to sleep with me again,

35:33.130 --> 35:34.090
I could live with that.

35:36.092 --> 35:40.096
That morning when
I called you on the boat...

35:40.179 --> 35:44.851
{\an5}(sighs)
all I really wanted to do
was hear your voice.

35:44.934 --> 35:46.978
Do you still want to?

35:48.062 --> 35:49.063
Yes.

36:10.585 --> 36:12.044
Hi, honey.

36:12.128 --> 36:14.422
Hi. Who won?

36:14.505 --> 36:15.506
{\an3}St(laughs)

36:15.590 --> 36:18.718
{\an3}He won $10,000 for sinking
a basket at halftime.

36:18.801 --> 36:20.094
$10,000? You're kidding.

36:20.177 --> 36:22.096
The Where is he?her.

36:22.179 --> 36:24.974
Oh, he and Brandon went down
to the Peach Pit to celebrate.

36:25.057 --> 36:26.601
{\an3}Why don't you go
down and join them?

36:26.684 --> 36:28.394
No, I think I'll just
stay here and read.

36:30.479 --> 36:32.398
Listen, honey...

36:32.481 --> 36:35.484
we know this has been
a rough time for you,

36:35.568 --> 36:38.988
{\an5}and... I mean, the last
thing we want to do is
to make it any rougher.

36:39.071 --> 36:41.073
And obviously,
you didn't feel comfortable

36:41.157 --> 36:43.075
talking to us about it, and...

36:43.159 --> 36:44.452
frankly, we feel
a little left out.

36:44.535 --> 36:47.830
{\an1}Look, I'm sorry,
but it's really no big deal.

36:47.914 --> 36:50.833
{\an1}I just feel more and more
like my real friends

36:50.917 --> 36:53.878
Well, you have real
arfriends here, too.a.

36:53.961 --> 36:56.088
Mom, I know, but it's different.

36:56.172 --> 36:57.465
{\an1}Back there, people
liked me for who I was,

36:57.548 --> 37:00.092
not what I looked like.

37:00.176 --> 37:02.094
{\an1}I don't know, somehow
it's not the same.

37:02.178 --> 37:04.972
Are you sorry we moved here?

37:05.056 --> 37:06.974
{\an1}No. I'm just
beginning to realize

37:07.058 --> 37:09.936
{\an1}that maybe I'm more Minnesota
than Beverly Hills.

37:10.019 --> 37:12.980
{\an6}(laughs)
Well, I think we all
feel that way sometimes.

37:13.064 --> 37:16.484
And as far as college goes, I...
I think your mom and I agree

37:16.567 --> 37:18.319
that... well,
it's probably smart that

37:18.402 --> 37:20.446
you keep your
options open.

37:20.529 --> 37:23.032
Well, while you guys were
at the game, I mailed in

37:23.115 --> 37:24.492
Good for you.n.

37:24.575 --> 37:27.662
And whether it's California or
Minnesota, we think either state

37:27.745 --> 37:28.412
{\an3}would be lucky
to have you.

37:35.753 --> 37:37.463
(door opens)

37:45.429 --> 37:47.848
So, do I still have a mom?

37:47.932 --> 37:49.934
Oh, baby.

37:52.269 --> 37:54.188
{\an3}Of course,

37:54.271 --> 37:56.273
of course.

37:57.566 --> 38:03.322
{\an6}(crying):
Not that I've been
much good to you.

38:03.406 --> 38:06.158
Kelly...

38:06.242 --> 38:10.162
{\an3}I'm so sorry for everything
I've put you through.

38:10.246 --> 38:13.416
Mom, it's not like
everything was bad.

38:13.499 --> 38:17.211
I... I just...

38:17.294 --> 38:20.297
wish I could
turn back the clock.

38:23.134 --> 38:26.012
{\an1}You were the one
good thing in my life,

38:26.095 --> 38:29.890
and like a selfish idiot,

38:29.974 --> 38:33.060
{\an1}I just kept
getting high and...

38:33.144 --> 38:35.271
running around and...

38:35.354 --> 38:37.606
{\an1}doing anything
but being a loving mom.

38:37.690 --> 38:41.068
{\an3}Well, you did the
best you could.

38:41.152 --> 38:43.904
{\an1}When I see you
beating yourself up...

38:43.988 --> 38:47.283
{\an1}I feel like
it's all my fault.

38:48.326 --> 38:50.369
{\an3}It can't be
all your fault--

38:50.453 --> 38:51.996
it's my life.

38:54.999 --> 38:59.253
{\an1}And I keep promising
things are gonna be different,

38:59.336 --> 39:00.755
and here we are,

39:00.838 --> 39:04.258
{\an1}me on my umpteenth
divorce and...

39:04.341 --> 39:07.303
you passing out
from diet pills.

39:09.180 --> 39:10.931
I was thinking,

39:11.015 --> 39:14.602
{\an3}maybe I should go back to
that eating disorder group.

39:14.685 --> 39:15.644
Maybe I could go with you.

39:15.728 --> 39:20.274
{\an1}Or maybe we could find
somebody to talk to about...

39:20.357 --> 39:23.110
{\an1}all the stuff we should've
dealt with years ago.

39:23.194 --> 39:27.281
I'd like to do
that with you.

39:27.364 --> 39:30.076
{\an3}I think it'd
be good for me.

39:30.159 --> 39:31.577
Me, too, honey.

39:31.660 --> 39:32.870
(laughs softly)

39:36.040 --> 39:37.166
Oh...

39:41.712 --> 39:43.297
STEVE:
<i>The basket looked</i>

39:43.380 --> 39:44.799
this big.

39:44.882 --> 39:45.508
What was it, uh, 70 feet?

39:45.591 --> 39:47.468
{\an3}170 feet, I
thought he said.

39:47.551 --> 39:51.180
{\an1}You guys,
just think about it.

39:51.263 --> 39:53.974
{\an1}What are the odds of <i> anyone</i>
making a shot like that?

39:54.058 --> 39:55.601
Mm, about the same as the odds

39:55.684 --> 39:59.355
of Celeste picking you over me
on that game show.

39:59.438 --> 40:01.982
Or the odds of Mrs. Teasley
writing you a glowing letter

40:02.066 --> 40:04.151
{\an3}of recommendation to the
California University.

40:04.235 --> 40:06.362
Or the odds of Hell
(Steve laughs)

40:06.445 --> 40:08.364
{\an1}You guys are all
missing the point.

40:08.447 --> 40:10.866
You see... it was my seat,

40:10.950 --> 40:14.829
it was <i> my</i> ticket stub,
it was <i> my</i> half-court shot, okay?

40:14.912 --> 40:15.830
All this on a night that

40:15.913 --> 40:18.833
{\an1}I thought would be
the biggest loser of all time.

40:18.916 --> 40:20.876
No offense.

40:20.960 --> 40:21.877
None taken.

40:21.961 --> 40:24.839
You see,
if I can make the shot,

40:24.922 --> 40:27.508
then it's got to be a sign,
like a new day or something.

40:27.591 --> 40:30.886
Like "Today is the first day
of the rest of your life"?

40:30.970 --> 40:33.722
And what are you gonna do for
the rest of your life, Steve?

40:33.806 --> 40:35.724
Well, one thing is for sure--
with these ten G's

40:35.808 --> 40:38.144
burning a hole in my pocket,

40:38.227 --> 40:40.855
I sure as <i> hell</i> ain't gonna
be slinging burgers this year.

40:40.938 --> 40:42.356
{\an3}Like you
would've anyway.

40:42.439 --> 40:43.691
{\an5}BRANDON:
Wait a minute,
Andrea, I thought

40:43.774 --> 40:46.485
you were gonna be running
that summer camp

40:46.569 --> 40:48.904
for the kids from
AYep, so did I,.

40:48.988 --> 40:50.531
{\an1}but Mrs. Teasley
informed me

40:50.614 --> 40:52.741
{\an1}that the school district
has pulled the plug.

40:52.825 --> 40:54.535
You're kiMm-mm.

40:54.618 --> 40:57.037
Mm, that's too bad..

40:57.121 --> 40:58.205
Those little kids
made my year

40:58.289 --> 41:01.208
when I was playing Santa Claus
for 'em last Christmas.

41:01.292 --> 41:03.377
That's 'cause they got him
out of detention.

41:03.460 --> 41:04.795
So <i> that</i> was the angle.

41:04.879 --> 41:06.088
What angle?

41:06.172 --> 41:08.090
I did not do it for that.

41:08.174 --> 41:11.093
{\an1}Relax, Steve-- it is
just a part of your charm.

41:11.177 --> 41:12.136
It's your basic karma, man.

41:12.219 --> 41:13.596
(forced chuckle)
All I could say is,

41:13.679 --> 41:16.557
ten years from now,
when you all have forgotten

41:16.640 --> 41:19.226
{\an3}what you won
You will have forgotten

41:19.310 --> 41:20.603
{\an3}what you blew
the ten G's on.

41:20.686 --> 41:22.605
Don't be so sure about that.

41:22.688 --> 41:25.107
{\an3}So what are you gonna
do with the money?

41:27.318 --> 41:30.112
I'm gonna spend it
all in one place.

41:32.823 --> 41:34.200
(laughs)

41:34.283 --> 41:36.035
(bell ringing)

41:36.118 --> 41:38.454
It was the strangest thing--
a messenger dropped off

41:38.537 --> 41:40.456
a certified check for $10,000,

41:40.539 --> 41:42.917
{\an1}payable to the Alvarado
Street Summer Camp.

41:43.000 --> 41:44.752
I can't believe it!

41:44.835 --> 41:46.921
So, Counselor,
you're back in business.

41:47.004 --> 41:48.923
{\an3}Oh, Mrs. Teasley, I
mean, this is amazing.

41:49.006 --> 41:51.383
That's the strange part.

41:51.467 --> 41:52.927
{\an1}The donor wished
to remain anonymous.

41:53.010 --> 41:56.597
{\an6}You know, you hear
about stuff like this--
a pure, unselfish gift.

41:56.680 --> 41:58.766
{\an3}Aren't you dying
to know who did it?

41:58.849 --> 42:00.142
Someone with $10,000.

42:00.226 --> 42:02.645
{\an3}I guess Santa Claus came
early this ye(laughs)

42:02.728 --> 42:06.232
(stops laughing)

42:11.153 --> 42:11.862
Nah.

42:26.043 --> 42:28.045
Your photographer awaits.

42:29.713 --> 42:32.216
You sure? 'Cause
we don't have to.

42:32.299 --> 42:34.426
{\an1}Zuckerman says we could
eliminate the whole category,

42:34.510 --> 42:36.971
and the world would be
a better place for it.

42:37.054 --> 42:38.264
No, I want to.

42:38.347 --> 42:40.849
{\an3}No tuxedos,
though, jusOkay.

42:40.933 --> 42:42.768
{\an1}Um, Kelly,

42:42.851 --> 42:45.688
{\an1}there's something
I want you to read.

42:45.771 --> 42:46.689
You don't have to.

42:46.772 --> 42:48.941
I know. I want to, though.

42:49.024 --> 42:51.694
{\an1}It's a, uh, first draft;
it's not finished.

42:51.777 --> 42:55.406
Well, I'll try not
to be too critical.

42:57.241 --> 42:59.159
"Dedicated to Kelly Taylor."

43:01.412 --> 43:03.330
So far I like it a lot.

43:06.292 --> 43:08.502
STEVE:
<i>The usher calls my seat.</i>

43:08.585 --> 43:09.837
{\an3}Instantly, I
was transformed

43:09.920 --> 43:10.796
{\an3}into a seven-foot-two
basketball player.

43:10.879 --> 43:13.132
{\an3}I walk down
on that court,

43:13.215 --> 43:14.842
{\an3}masquerading around in
my own little aura energy.

43:14.925 --> 43:17.386
{\an3}There was the basket,
no bigger than a pinhead.

43:17.469 --> 43:18.846
{\an3}Brenda, you haven't
heard this.

43:18.929 --> 43:20.848
{\an1}Yes, I did, Steve,
and congratulations.

43:20.931 --> 43:23.851
{\an6}No, he means you
haven't heard the
Sanders play-by-play.

43:23.934 --> 43:24.852
It's interminable.

43:24.935 --> 43:26.812
(sighs)
Do you haNo!a second?

43:26.895 --> 43:31.191
Brenda is my friend, and I will
not let you bore her to death.

43:31.275 --> 43:33.694
{\an1}Donna, actually,
I'd like to hear it.

43:33.777 --> 43:35.362
Okay.

43:35.446 --> 43:36.739
Thank you. There I was,
I walked out on the court,

43:36.822 --> 43:38.824
the picture of calmness--
I was cool, I was mellow.

43:38.907 --> 43:41.994
It was a Zen thing.
I had the ball in my hand.

43:42.077 --> 43:43.871
I wanted to breathe
through my eyes...

43:43.954 --> 43:47.082
{\an5}DYLAN:
<i>Even before he noticed her,</i>
<i>he noticed her boat,</i>

43:47.166 --> 43:49.585
<i>a sleek two-footer</i>
<i>she had been given</i>

43:49.668 --> 43:52.129
<i>for her fifth birthday</i>
<i>a few days before.</i>

43:52.212 --> 43:53.964
<i>She was sailing it, upside down</i>

43:54.048 --> 43:57.718
<i>in a large pool that had formed</i>
<i>during a winter rain.</i>

43:57.801 --> 44:01.055
<i>The rain, again.</i>

44:01.138 --> 44:03.015
<i>In a marina this time.</i>

44:03.098 --> 44:05.893
<i>The boats, like the girl,</i>
<i>had grown.</i>

44:05.976 --> 44:08.937
<i>Beautiful, inspirational.</i>

44:09.021 --> 44:12.191
<i>After the explosion</i>
<i>that killed his father,</i>

44:12.274 --> 44:15.569
<i>she was the only beauty,</i>
<i>the only inspiration,</i>

44:15.652 --> 44:18.113
<i>left in his life.</i>

44:20.866 --> 44:25.120
{\an3}Dylan, did you mean
what you said yesterday?

44:25.204 --> 44:26.955
{\an1}We said a lot
of things, Kel.

44:27.039 --> 44:30.918
{\an3}The part about how if we
never slept together again

44:31.001 --> 44:32.920
you could live with that?

44:33.003 --> 44:33.796
Are you sure I said that?

44:33.879 --> 44:36.006
{\an1}I mean, it just doesn't
sound like me.

44:36.090 --> 44:38.175
BOY:
All righty.

44:38.258 --> 44:39.593
Here we go. Smile.

44:42.721 --> 44:43.764
(shutter clicks)
